03/04/2011
ANKARA, Turkey -- Turkish parliament passed a law on Thursday (March 31st) that foresees tougher sanctions for football hooliganism and match fixing. 
The new measures envision up to six years in prison for soccer fans that break seats at the stadiums, two years imprisonment for those chanting racist slogans and up to one year in prison for the fans who try to enter the stadiums with guns or sharp objects. 
A prison term of up to 12 years in envisaged for match-fixing. 
The law also introduces an electronic ticket for the football matches containing person's data. 
(Hurriyet, Anadolu news agency, MIA - 01/04/11)
